draw(C--D--H--G--C);
draw(D--A--E--H--D);
draw(A--B--F--E--A);
draw(Circle((0.5,0.5,0),0.5),dashed);

label("$r$", (0.5,0.5,0), S);
label("$h$", (0.5,0.5,0.5), W);
[/asy]

Then the prism has volume $V_{\text{prism}} = BCDE \cdot h,$ and the cone has volume $V_{\text{cone}} = \frac{1}{3} \pi r^2 h.$

Note that $BCDE$ is the cross section of the prism, so the height of the cone is $h$ as well.  Also, the radius of the cone is half the height of the cross section of the prism, so $r = \frac{1}{2} BC = \frac{1}{2} DE.$

Thus, the ratio of the volume of the cone to the volume of the prism is $$\frac{V_{\text{cone}}}{V_{\text{prism}}} = \frac{\frac{1}{3} \pi \left( \frac{1}{2} DE \right)^2 h}{BCDE \cdot h} = \frac{\frac{1}{3} \pi \cdot \frac{1}{4} BC^2}{BCDE} = \boxed{\frac{\pi}{12}}.$$

